ElementDescription: The NDAR Global Unique Identifier (GUID) for research subject
Subject ID how it's defined in lab/project
Date on which the interview/genetic test/sampling/imaging/biospecimen was completed. MM/DD/YYYY
Age in months at the time of the interview/test/sampling/imaging.
Notes: Age is rounded to chronological month. If the research participant is 15-days-old at time of interview, the appropriate value would be 0 months. If the participant is 16-days-old, the value would be 1 month.

ElementDescription: Sex of subject at birth
Notes: M = Male; F = Female; O=Other; NR = Not reported

ElementDescription: Do you get upset if your child eats too little?
Do you worry that your child is currently underweight?
Do you worry that your child will become underweight?
Is it difficult to get your child to eat new foods?
Is your child a picky eater?
Do you make special meals for your child because he/she is a picky eater?
Is it a struggle to get your child to eat?
Does your child frequently have a poor appetite?
Do you get upset if your child does not eat enough?
Does your child eat a very limited variety of food?
Does your child only eat foods if they are prepared in a specific way?
Does your child often express a strong dislike for food?
Mean score of the Avoidant/Restrictive Food Intake Disorder (ARFID) subscale
Notes: Mean average of responses for items sfq_arfid_1 through sfq_arfid_12

ElementDescription: Do you offer foods your child likes (for example: candy, ice cream, cakes, pastries) as a reward for eating foods that are good for him/her?
Do you make your child finish all his/her dinner before she/he can have a dessert?
When the family eats dinner together do you often plan a separate food for your child?
Do you argue with your spouse about your child's eating habits or food selection?
Do you often soothe your child by giving him/her something to eat or drink
Do you often give your child something to eat or drink if he/she is bored, even if you think he/she is not hungry?
Do you often give your child something to eat to stop a temper tantrum?
Do you offer your child his/her favorite foods in exchange for good behavior?
Do you use food to occupy your child while you are attending to other matters?
At family meals do you let your child choose the foods he/she wants from what is served?
Do you make something different if your child does not like what is being served?
Do you feed your child yourself if he/she does not eat enough?
Do you give your child bottles of juice or milk in the car?
Do you give your child bottles of juice or milk in his/her bed?
If your child wakes at night do you feed him/her to help him/her fall back to sleep?
Mean score of the Parental Feeding Problems (PFP) subscale
Notes: Mean average of responses for items sfq_pfp_1 through sfq_pfp_15

ElementDescription: Timepoint/visit label
Notes: e.g., Baseline, 6-Month Follow Up, Year 2; Morning, At Bedtime
